      <bioghist id="aspace_e31285b4e031312889abdb83b35f2385">
         <head>William Peterfield Trent (1862-1939)</head>
         <p>William Peterfield Trent was born in Richmond, Virginia on November 10, 1862. He received his M.A. from the University of Virginia in 1884 and his LL.B from Wake Forest College in 1889. He joined the faculty of Sewanee, The University of the South as a professor of English in 1888. While there, he founded and edited <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>The Sewanee Review</part>
            </title> (1892), founded the Sewanee Historical Society, and published several works, including the <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Life of William Gilmore Simms</part>
            </title> (1892).</p>
         <p>In 1900 he moved to Columbia University as a professor of English and taught there until his retirement in 1929. His works include <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>A History of American Literature, 1607-1865</part>
            </title> (1903); <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Longfellow and Other Essays</part>
            </title> (1910); and <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Defoe--How to Know Him</part>
            </title> (1916). He was co-editor of the Columbia University edition of the complete works of John Milton (1931), and of the <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Cambridge History of American Literature</part>
            </title> (1917-1921). He also contributed articles on Defoe and other eighteenth-century authors to the <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Cambridge History of English Literature</part>
            </title> (1932).</p>
         <p>For over fifteen years, Trent worked on a multi-volume bibliography of Daniel Defoe, as well as an accompanying biography. These works were never completed or published, although Yale Professor of English and Defoe scholar Henry Clinton Hutchins (1889-1962) carried out additional editorial work on Trent's materials during the 1930s and 1940s.</p>
         <p>Trent married Alice Lyman in 1896, and the couple had two children, Lucia Trent Chaney and William P. Trent, Jr. He died, after several years of poor health, at home in Hopewell Junction, New York on December 7, 1939.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_52278824a59614704e0986aeee687bc8">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>Notes, newspaper clippings, manuscripts, typescripts, and printed material related to William Peterfield Trent's unpublished biography and bibliography of Daniel Defoe; and correspondence, notes, and printed material related to Henry Clinton Hutchins's editorial work on Trent's manuscripts.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_84be4da34fe0043532e8f9a39de54be3">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Organized into two groupings: I. William Peterfield Trent Research Materials, 1912-1939; II. Henry Clinton Hutchins Research Materials, 1830-1962.</p>  
      </arrangement>
